    industryNorms: `ANSI A300 governs pruning, support systems, and integrated vegetation management; ANSI Z133 governs arboricultural safety. ISA Certified Arborist, TRAQ (Tree Risk Assessment Qualification), and BCMA are the credential ladder. TCIA accreditation is the company-level trust signal. OSHA regulates tree care operations and the Line Clearance Tree Trimmer (LCTT) qualification is mandatory for work within 10 ft of energized conductors — only qualified LCTT crews can touch utility lines. State licensing varies: CA C-61/D-49, CT, LA, MD, ME, MA, NJ (registered tree expert), RI require state arborist licensing. Pesticide application requires state applicator licensing. Canadian Ontario MOL + Working at Heights regulates tree care; municipal bylaws (Toronto, Vancouver, much of CA) require permits for removal of large or heritage trees with penalties up to $10,000+ per tree. Boulevard/right-of-way trees are city property.`,
    commonChallenges: `Storm-chaser door-knockers post-storm undercut local reputable companies — counter with ISA + TCIA marketing. Topping requests are constant and must be politely refused per ANSI A300. Neighbor tree disputes (overhanging branches, root damage) require working only with the tree-owner's consent. HOA and municipal permit confusion — coach the owner on who pulls the permit and when heritage tree rules apply. Insurance coverage misunderstanding: covered damage caused by a tree vs uncovered preventive removal is the conversation. Weather windows for tree work are tight in storm season; coach the owner on scheduling discipline so emergency calls don't bury routine work. Cleanup expectations (wood, chips, rake-out) must be in writing or callbacks will eat the margin.`,
